0[1] RFC-1436	/archive/rfc/1436.txt
i		gopher.black	70
iWhy use type i gophermaps for things like this phlog? It makes it		gopher.black	70
ieasy to link to things, like the RFC above. I could drop in		gopher.black	70
ia gopher URL instead, but wait... those didn't exist when RFC-1436		gopher.black	70
icame out either. So should I instead list a selector, server, and		gopher.black	70
iport? Oh, I better indicate a type as well. No, that's silly. Even		gopher.black	70
ithough the URL scheme came later it's a useful convention. It		gopher.black	70
imakes it easier for other people. See where I'm going?		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iSo why NOT use type i in this way? Well, two reasons. First, it's		gopher.black	70
iharder to lay out. Working in gophermaps is nasty business.		gopher.black	70
iI wrote a tool[2] to do it for me. Without that I wouldn't do it.		gopher.black	70
iIt's easy to screw up and awful to edit later. Easier just to		gopher.black	70
iwrite plain text, and plain text is sufficient.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
h[2] Burrow	URL:https://github.com/jamestomasino/burrow
i		gopher.black	70
iAnd the second reason? Very old clients like the original UMN		gopher.black	70
igopher client don't work well with them.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iThankfully very few people use that client anynmore because it's		gopher.black	70
ipretty janky and has barely been maintained. Last I heard it was		gopher.black	70
iin search of a new maintainer, actually. And these days we have		gopher.black	70
ia wealth of new clients that are simply fantastic. We have the		gopher.black	70
